    "I feel the most critical issues/challenges currently facing design are:__1": "Stepping back from all the advancements of our time and paying attention to people and how they live their day to day lives it's shocking how sucked into devices people are. While they are tools to make our lives better we are wired to the default of looking into our phone when we are bored and going down the rabbit hole of notifications among other things. That's a dangerous place to be in. How do we make sure we are working for the users while also moving the business forward (to get that seat at the table)? It's a tricky, fine line that many designers face. Additionally, a problem not mentioned in the previous question is access to salaried design work. It's evident that design is in high demand, but the lack of desire to hire and train newer designers is not. Many companies will trash applications that demonstrate little work experience through ATS. Or their job listing itself will ask for a minimum of four years and many people will not apply to it out of feeling unqualified. Junior designers should be sought out and trained because in a few years they will be the industry. There are a plethora of design jobs out there, but they all want people that have been present in the industry for years... that's a small selection of people vs the number of junior designers that want to put in the work and want to get better. There are plenty of issues in design; based on where you are in your career and the kind of industry you work in, some may not be noticeable. It's a matter of perspective.",
